{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486786"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"174"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/174"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.03,0.66,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81556"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/174"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66910"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"1961"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42016"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81556"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic accompanied by his family with a two-month history of behavioural changes. He believes he can control the weather, that his cows are talking to him, and that the television and sun are sending him messages from God. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus. His only medication is metformin. He works as a farmer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears dishevelled with poor personal hygiene. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His speech is disorganised and difficult to follow. His BMI is 29 kg/m2. His property has fallen into disrepair.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antipsychotic medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Olanzapine","Clozapine","Aripiprazole","Haloperidol","Lithium"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with first episode psychosis, characterised by delusions (controlling weather, messages from God), hallucinations (talking cows), disorganised speech, and negative symptoms (poor self-care). The two-month duration suggests schizophreniform disorder rather than schizophrenia, which requires six months of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAripiprazole\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice given his pre-existing metabolic risk factors (type 2 diabetes, elevated BMI). It is a second-generation antipsychotic with a lower risk of weight gain and metabolic side effects compared to other options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlanzapine\u003C/strong\u003E, while effective, carries a high risk of weight gain and metabolic complications, making it a poor choice for someone with existing diabetes and weight concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClozapine\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for treatment-resistant cases where at least two other antipsychotics have failed. It requires regular blood monitoring and carries significant side effect risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E, a first-generation antipsychotic, has a higher risk of extrapyramidal side effects and is not preferred as first-line treatment when second-generation options are available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELithium\u003C/strong\u003E is a mood stabiliser used primarily in bipolar disorder. It is not indicated for primary psychotic disorders in the absence of significant mood symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First episode psychosis should be treated with second-generation antipsychotics due to their superior side effect profile.","Aripiprazole has a lower risk of metabolic side effects compared to other antipsychotics, making it preferred in patients with diabetes or obesity.","The presence of delusions, hallucinations, and disorganised speech for less than 6 months suggests schizophreniform disorder."],"references":["Galletly C, Castle D, Dark F et al. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists clinical practice guidelines for the management of schizophrenia and related disorders. Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry. 2016; 50(5): 1-117.","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66910"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"174"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66910"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T12:02:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T12:03:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"174"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81556"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attrib